**Object.keys()**

 1. `Object.keys()` will create an array of keys for the object that is in variable `object` 
 2. `find()` will find the matching key that matches the condition. In your case, matching the `toSearch` text inside the array values of that key, for which you can use `includes()` or even `indexOf(toSearch) !== -1`

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var object = { &quot;a&quot; : [], &quot;b&quot; : [&quot;S&quot;,&quot;W&quot;], &quot;c&quot; : [&quot;N&quot;,&quot;E&quot;]};
    var toSearch = &#39;S&#39;;
    var key = Object.keys(object).find((key) =&gt; object[key].includes(toSearch));
    console.log(key);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can also use another way using `Object.entries()` like:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var object = { &quot;a&quot; : [], &quot;b&quot; : [&quot;S&quot;,&quot;W&quot;], &quot;c&quot; : [&quot;N&quot;,&quot;E&quot;]};
    var toSearch = &#39;S&#39;;
    var key = (Object.entries(object).find(([key, value]) =&gt; value.includes(toSearch)) || [])[0];
    console.log(key);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

